Finer-scale analyses reveal that SNP only has a little over one-third of its area as intact forest, while another one-third was identified as non-intact forest (Fig. 10
                        ). While the accuracy of each of the three classifications for SNP differ (Table 1
                        ), the overall proportion of the three land covers as identified by the three classified maps are somewhat similar. Intact forest area ranged between 38.6% and 41.2% of the total park area, closely followed by non-intact forest ranging between 36.8% and 40.3%, depending on data combinations. Non-forest, i.e. completely cleared area, ranged between 21% and 23.1%. The classified map derived from Sentinel-2 data had the highest overall accuracy of 87%, with kappa coefficient (Cohen, 1960) of 0.80 (Table 1). We also ran the classifier for Sentinel-2 data rescaled at 20 m. However, the classified maps for both PAs are similar to the maps generated by the Sentinel 2 data at 10 m, both in terms of spatial distribution and areas under different land covers. The PoA approach reveals that all three classifications identified approximately 36% of area in SNP as either non-intact forest or non-forest (Fig. 10).
